<section xml:id="section-complex-matrices-terminology">

<title>Terminology and notation</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title>complex linear equation</title>
		<idx><h>complex</h><h>linear equation</h></idx>
		<idx><h>linear</h><h>equation</h><h>complex</h></idx>
		<idx><h>equation(s)</h><h>linear</h><h>complex</h></idx>
		<p>a linear equation where the coefficients are complex numbers and the variables are allowed to take on complex values</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>complex matrix</title>
		<idx><h>complex</h><h>matrix</h></idx>
		<idx><h>matrix</h><h>complex</h></idx>
		<p>a matrix whose entries are complex numbers</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<remark><p>
	Remember that a real number is just a special kind of complex number. Therefore,
	<ul>
		<li>
			every linear equation with real coefficients can be considered as a complex linear equation by allowing the variables involved to take on complex values;
			and
		</li>
		<li> every matrix whose entries are real numbers can also be considered as a complex matrix. </li>
	</ul>
</p></remark>

<p><dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title>complex conjugate of a matrix <m>A</m></title>
		<idx><h>complex</h><h>matrix</h><h>conjugate</h></idx>
		<idx><h>matrix</h><h>complex</h><h>conjugate</h></idx>
		<p> the matrix <m>\cconj{A}</m> obtained by replacing each entry by its complex conjugate </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>(complex) adjoint of a matrix <m>A</m></title>
		<idx><h>complex</h><h>matrix</h><h>adjoint</h></idx>
		<idx><h>matrix</h><h>complex</h><h>adjoint</h></idx>
		<p>
			the matrix <m>\adjoint{A}</m> obtained by taking the transpose of the conjugate of <m>A</m>,
			<ie /> <m>\adjoint{A} = \utrans{\cconj{A}}</m>
		</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>self-adjoint matrix</title>
		<idx><h>complex</h><h>matrix</h><h>self-adjoint</h></idx>
		<idx><h>matrix</h><h>self-adjoint</h></idx>
		<p>
			a complex matrix that is equal to its own complex adjoint;
			also referred to as a
			<term>Hermitian matrix</term>
			<idx><h>complex</h><h>matrix</h><h>Hermitian</h></idx>
			<idx><h>matrix</h><h>Hermitian</h></idx>
		</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<warning><p>
	Do not confuse the complex adjoint of a matrix with the classical adjoint studied in
	<xref ref="chapter-more-det" />.
</p></warning>

